Request Lifecycle 

When write kubectl apply -f pod.yaml, then these 7 steps happens:

The 7 Steps
Step	        Name	        Simple Meaning	                    Fail Result
1	            TLS	            Check if connection is secure	    Request dropped
2	            Authentication	Who are you? Check your ID	        401 Unauthorized
3	            Authorization	Can you do this? Check permissions	403 Forbidden
4	            Mutating	    Modify YAML if needed (add defaults, sidecars)	-
5	            Schema	        Check spelling and structure	    Request blocked
6	            Validating	    Final policy check (allow or deny)	Request denied
7	            etcd	        Save permanently in database	    -


Two Background Processes
After saving in etcd, API Server does two things automatically:

1. Watch API
API Server tells scheduler instantly: "New pod needs a node."
Real benefit: No waiting. Instant response.

2. Optimistic Concurrency Control
If two people update same object at same time, only first wins. Second gets 409 conflict error.

Real benefit: No data corruption.

